Term Deposit Sale - Bank Marketing¶

Domain:¶

Banking

Data Description:¶

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be ('yes') or not ('no') subscribed.

[Moro et al., 2014] S. Moro, P. Cortez and P. Rita. A Data-Driven Approach to Predict the Success of Bank Telemarketing. Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 62:22-31, June 2014

https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing

Attributes Information:¶

Bank client data:¶

  • age: numeric
  • job: : categorical, type of job ('admin.', 'blue-collar', 'entrepreneur', 'housemaid', 'management', 'retired', 'self-employed', 'services', 'student', 'technician', 'unemployed', 'unknown')
  • marital: : categorical, marital status ('divorced', 'married', 'single', 'unknown'). 'divorced' means divorced or widowed.
  • education: categorical, education level ('tertiary', 'secondary', 'unknown', 'primary')
  • default: categorical, has credit in default? ('no','yes','unknown')
  • housing: categorical, has housing loan? ('no','yes','unknown')
  • loan: categorical, has personal loan? ('no','yes','unknown')
  • balance: balance in account

Related with the last contact of the current campaign:¶

  • contact: categorical, contact communication type ('cellular', 'telephone')
  • month: categorical, last contact month of year ('jan', 'feb', 'mar', ..., 'nov', 'dec')
  • day: categorical, last contact day of the month
  • duration: numeric, last contact duration, in seconds.

Other attributes:¶

  • campaign: numeric, number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client
  • pdays: numeric, number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (-1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days)
  • previous: numeric, number of times the client has been contacted before to subscribe term deposit
  • poutcome: categorical, outcome of the previous marketing campaign ('failure', 'nonexistent', 'success')

Output variable:¶

  • Target: binary, desired target, has the client subscribed a term deposit? ('yes','no')

Goal:¶

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.

cat_bin_vars = ['default', 'housing', 'loan', 'Target']

def plot_counts_percentages(data, col):
    total_clients = data.shape[0]
    chart = sns.countplot(data[col], order = ['yes', 'no'], palette=['mediumseagreen', 'tomato']);
    chart.set(title=col.title(), xlabel='', ylabel='Count')
    for p in chart.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        chart.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2., height + 3, '{:1.2f}'.format((height/total_clients)*100), ha='center') 

def display_pair(data, col1, col2):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plot_counts_percentages(data, col1)
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plot_counts_percentages(data, col2)
    
    plt.show()
    
pairs = np.array(cat_bin_vars).reshape((2,2))
   
for cat_cols in pairs:
    display_pair(df, cat_cols[0], cat_cols[1])

plt.pie(
        [df[df['Target'] == 'yes']['Target'].count(), df[df['Target'] == 'no']['Target'].count()],
        explode = (0.1, 0),
        labels = sorted(df['Target'].unique(), reverse=True),
        colors = ['mediumseagreen', 'tomato'],
        autopct='%1.1f%%',
        shadow=True,
        startangle=140,
        pctdistance=0.5,
        labeldistance=1.1)
plt.axis('equal')
plt.title('Target - Relative frequency')
plt.show()    
    
for cat_col in cat_bin_vars:
    print(cat_col)
    print(df[cat_col].value_counts())
    print()

cat_vars = ['marital', 'education', 'poutcome', 'contact']

def plot_counts_percentages(data, col, vr=0):
    total_clients = data.shape[0]
    chart = sns.countplot(data[col], order = data[col].value_counts().index, palette='muted');
    chart.set(title=col.title(), xlabel='', ylabel='Count')
    chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(),  rotation=vr)
    for p in chart.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        chart.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2., height + 3, '{:1.2f}'.format((height/total_clients)*100), ha='center') 

def display_pair(data, col1, col2):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plot_counts_percentages(data, col1)
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plot_counts_percentages(data, col2)
    
    plt.show()

pairs = np.array(cat_vars).reshape((2,2))
  
for cat_cols in pairs:

def display_num_stats(data, col, hist_color='seagreen', box_color='steelblue'):
    f = plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    gs = f.add_gridspec(1, 2)

    with sns.axes_style("whitegrid"):
        ax = f.add_subplot(gs[0, 0])
        sns.distplot(data[col], color=hist_color, kde=True, rug=True)

    with sns.axes_style("darkgrid"):
        ax = f.add_subplot(gs[0, 1])
        sns.boxplot(x=data[col], notch = True, color=box_color)
    
    f.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    # Computing IQR
    Q1 = data[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    LWhisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    UWhisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    UpperOutliers = data[data[col] > UWhisker][col].count();
    LowerOutliers = data[data[col] < LWhisker][col].count();

    print(col.title())
    print('Skew:', data[col].skew())
    print('Lower whisker', LWhisker)
    print('Upper whisker', UWhisker)
    print('Outliers above upper whisker: ', UpperOutliers, '({:.1f}%)'.format( (UpperOutliers/data.shape[0])*100) )
    print('Outliers under lower whisker: ', LowerOutliers, '({:.1f}%)'.format( (LowerOutliers/data.shape[0])*100) )

def get_count_percentage_df(df, col, value):
    matching_count = len(df[df[col] == value])
    percentage_of_total = (matching_count/len(df.index)) * 100
    return [matching_count, percentage_of_total]

def get_count_percentage_s(s, value):
    matching_count = len(s[s == value])
    percentage_of_total = (matching_count/len(s)) * 100
    return [matching_count, percentage_of_total]

Define Utility Functions¶

In [115]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, roc_curve

def report_ROC(estimator, x_te, y_te, roc_auc, title, force_show=True):
    #plt.figure()
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_te, estimator.predict_proba(x_te)[:,1])
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='{} (area = {:0.2f})'.format(title, roc_auc))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    if(force_show):
        plt.show()
        
    return {'fpr': fpr, 'tpr':tpr, 'thresholds': thresholds, 'roc_auc': roc_auc}
In [116]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

def cm_report(cm, title, report, force_show=True):
    flat_cm = cm.flatten();
    group_names = ['TN', 'FP', 'FN', 'TP']
    group_counts = ['{}'.format(value) for value in flat_cm]
    labels = [f'{v1}\n{v2}' for v1, v2 in zip(group_names, group_counts)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    color_map = { flat_cm[0]:'mediumseagreen', flat_cm[1]:'tomato', flat_cm[2]:'tomato', flat_cm[3]:'mediumseagreen'}
    colors =  [(color_map[index] if index in color_map.keys() else 'black') for index in np.arange(flat_cm.min(), flat_cm.max() + 1)] 
    
    #plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt='', xticklabels = [0, 1], yticklabels = [0, 1], cmap=colors, cbar = False, annot_kws={"size": 20})
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    if(force_show):
        plt.show()
    
    TP = cm.flatten()[3]
    TN = cm.flatten()[0]
    FP = cm.flatten()[1]
    FN = cm.flatten()[2]

    recall = TP/(TP + FN)
    specificity = TN/(FP + TN)
    precision = TP/(TP + FP)
    accuracy = (TP + TN)/(TP + TN + FP + FN)
    error_rate = 1 - accuracy
    
    report['Accuracy-testing'] = accuracy
    report['Precision'] = precision
    report['Recall/Sensitivity/TPR'] = recall
    report['Specificity/TNR'] = specificity
    report['Error Rate'] = error_rate
    report['TP'] = TP
    report['TN'] = TN
    report['FP'] = FP
    report['FN'] = FN
    
    return report

from sklearn.metrics import recall_score, precision_score, f1_score, accuracy_score, classification_report

def estimator_report(estimator, title, x_tr, y_tr, x_te, y_te):
    y_pred = estimator.predict(x_te)
    
    # Other ways
    # print('Training Accuracy      : ', estimator.score(x_tr, y_tr))
    # print('Testing  Accuracy      : ', estimator.score(x_te, y_te))
    # accuracy_score(y_test, y_predict)
    # classification_report(y_test, y_predict)
    # print('Recall          :', recall_score(y_test, y_predict))
    # print('Precision       :', precision_score(y_test, y_predict))
    # print('F1 Score        :', f1_score(y_test, y_predict))
    # print('Roc Auc Score   :', roc_auc_score(y_test, y_predict))

    accuracy_training = estimator.score(x_tr, y_tr)
    f1 = f1_score(y_te, y_pred)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_te, y_pred)
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_te, estimator.predict(x_te))
    
    estimator_cm_report = pd.DataFrame(
        [[accuracy_training, -1, -1, -1, -1, roc_auc, f1, -1, -1, -1, -1, -1]],
        columns=['Accuracy-training', 'Accuracy-testing', 'Precision', 'Recall/Sensitivity/TPR', 'Specificity/TNR', 'ROC AUC', 'F1', 'Error Rate', 'TP', 'TN', 'FP', 'FN'],
        index=[title]
    )

    # Confusion matrix & ROC AUC
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    estimator_cm_report = cm_report(cm, title, estimator_cm_report, False)

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    roc_report = report_ROC(estimator, x_te, y_te, roc_auc, title, force_show=False)
   
    plt.show()
    

    # Feature Importance
    coeff = []
    if hasattr(estimator, 'feature_importances_'):
        coeff = estimator.feature_importances_
    elif hasattr(estimator, 'coef_'):
        coeff = abs(estimator.coef_[0])

    if len(coeff) > 0:
        fi_df = pd.DataFrame(coeff, columns = ['Importance'], index = x_tr.columns).sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False).reset_index()
        fi_df.rename(columns = {'index': 'Feature'}, inplace=True)
        display(fi_df.head(5))

        chart = sns.barplot(x='Feature', y='Importance', data=fi_df, palette='Reds_r')
        chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(),  rotation=90)
        chart.set(title='Feature Importance',  xlabel='', ylabel='')
        plt.show()
    
    return {'cm': estimator_cm_report, 'roc': roc_report, 'fi':fi_df if len(coeff) > 0 else None , 'title': title}
In [118]:
def draw_combined_ROC(reports):
    line_colors = ['r', 'g', 'b', 'm', 'darkorange', 'dimgray', 'c', 'black', 'black']
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    for index, report in enumerate(reports):
        fpr = report['roc']['fpr']
        tpr = report['roc']['tpr']
        roc_auc = report['roc']['roc_auc']
        title = report['title']
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='{} (area = {:0.2f})'.format(title, roc_auc), color=line_colors[index])

    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

Insights:

  • LogisticRegration from sklearn uses P > 0.5 as the theshold for classification.
  • We got slightly better results with newton-cg solver.
  • Accuracy is almost at its best - 0.88. Hence Error Rate is 0.12.
  • Precision is the ratio TP / (TP + FP). This is the ability of the classifier not to label as positive a sample that is negative. The best value is 1 and the worst value is 0. We have roughly 0.59, which is not good.
  • Reacall is the ratio TP / (TP + FN). This is the ability of the classifier to find all the positive samples. The best value is 1 and the worst value is 0. We have roughly ~0.21, the worst result.
  • The F1 score can be interpreted as a weighted average of the precision and recall, an F1 score reaches its best at 1 and worst score at 0. As expected, we have roughly 0.30, very bad overall.
  • Roc Auc Score Area under the curve, this performance metric describes our model itself, it is classification threshold invariant. The best value is 1 and the worst value is 0. Area is 0.59 for our model's performance, we have 59% of correct predictions, which is almost random.

  • Specificity, we are very good at predicting people who won't accept subscribtions. We have roughly 0.99.

  • TP (True Positives): correctly predicted 329 people who subscribed a term deposit.

  • TN (True Negatives): correctly predicted 11648 people who didn't subscribe a term deposit.

  • FP (False Positives): incorrectly predicted 229 people to subscrib a term deposit, but they did not. Type I error

  • FN (False Negatives): incorrectly predicted 1271 people to not subscribe a term deposit, but they did. Type II error

5. Conclusions¶

  • XGBClassifier gave us the best results, so let's discuss it below.
  • Model comments
  1. Interestingly: Clients who had been contacted during last campaign have additional data expressed in columns: poutcome, previous and pdays. If we think about it we could have a separate model for this subset of clients, or somehow let an overall model know how to split the data.
  2. Duration highly affects the output Target, if duration = 0 then Traget = 'no'. Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call Traget is obviously known. Because our task is to predict future outcome we could discard this variable to get a more realistic predictive model.
  • Model outcomes

  • It is important to mention that there is some disbalance in the initial dataset, we have only 11.7% cases of people who subscribed a term deposit, and therefore 88.3% of people who did not.

  • Consequently, in our model we got very good at detecting people who won't accept subscribe a term deposit (Specificity - 0.96).

  • Dispite the disbalance, we still managed to achive Max Recall of ~0.49, which is not completely bad. If we want to get better at predicting potential subscribers we want more data on succesful aceptance.

  • F1 score gives us hormonic mean for TPR & FPR and shows us how good we did at predicting people who subscribes a term deposit, ~0.55 out of 1.

  • Important Features

The top 6 of most influencial features for the model's output. Based on the feature importance values.

  1. Contact
  2. Housing
  3. Duration
  4. Previous
  5. Month
  6. Job

Interestingly, Education, Balance and Age have low importance.

AUC metric tells us, that our model has correct predictions in 72% of the cases, which can be considered an OK result for use in bank's term deposit campaigns.

Overall our model can provide value to the bank.
